N2  -  Abstract : Presented at the 2024 NYC Neuromodulation Conference Synopsis In a nationally‐recruiting, multi‐center sham‐controlled RCT we have demonstrated the feasibility and scalability of using remotely supervised transcranial direct current stimulation (RS‐tDCS) to provide contactless tDCS interventions from a central location. Through the NIH RECOVER‐ NEURO initiative, this five‐arm RCT is testing interventions for cognitive dysfunction in patients with post‐acute sequelae of SARS‐CoV‐2 infection (PASC)[1]. Two of the five arms were interventions using tDCS, with active or sham tDCS delivered for 50 sessions over 10 weeks. These arms reached n=131 enrolled tDCS arm participants within nine months, enrolling cross 22 centers across the U.S. All tDCS intervention is conducted completely via video visits through the central NYU Langone Health tDCS program site. Background Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) requires large‐scale randomized controlled trials (RCTs) to advance it to clinical use, particularly as it requires repeated daily session dosing over extended periods to evaluate its effects accurately. To date, most clinical trials of tDCS have been limited in sample size and number of treatment sessions because patient participants have been required to travel to a clinic to receive treatment. Over the past 10 years, the NYU group has developed the remotely supervised transcranial direct current stimulation (RS‐tDCS) protocol to overcome these barriers[2–4]. Here, we demonstrate how it can be broadly scalable to facilitate large and rapidly recruiting multi‐center RCTs with extended dosing paradigms. The NIH RECOVER‐NEURO initiative is conducting a five‐arm RCT, evaluating interventions to remediate the cognitive dysfunction that occurs in post‐acute sequelae of SARS‐CoV‐2 infection (PASC), or long COVID[1]. Two of the five arms include tDCS (active or sham) paired with cognitive training (BrainHQ). Methods Participants were enrolled from centers across the U.S. and randomly assigned to a treatment arm, with all intervention delivered as contactless treatment through our NYU Langone Health central location. Participants randomized to the tDCS arms received either active or sham stimulation. The tDCS equipment, including device, headgear, and single‐use sponge electrodes, was shipped directly to participants. The devices were pre‐programmed to deliver a 2.0 mA current for 30 minutes per session, five times a week for 10 weeks, totaling 50 sessions[1]. Participants first had an intake visit where they were provided with an orientation to tDCS equipment and complete tolerability test. This was followed by daily (M‐F) treatment sessions, each session began with a safety check and visual confirmation of correct headset placement via a HIPAA‐compliant video visit. Participants then used a one‐time‐use unlock code provided by the supervising technician to start each daily session. Real‐time monitoring ensured adherence and proper device use, and data were collected remotely to track session completion and participant feedback. Results Within nine months, we reached n=131 participants enrolled to a tDCS arm through 22 centers across the U.S For the tDCS arms: average time to initiate contact with participants from when they were randomized was 3.51 +/‐ 1.60 days. We then shipped the equipment to their home location, resulting in an average time to initiate intervention of 9.56 +/‐ 3.45 days. Discussion This trial demonstrates the feasibility and scalability of home‐based RS‐tDCS protocol for use in large scale and nationally‐recruiting RCTs. The extended dosing paradigm of 50 sessions highlights the potential for evaluating the cumulative effect of tDCS and overcoming limitations of potential under‐dosing in previous clinical trials[5,6]. A central and contactless delivery of tDCS is feasible for large‐scale studies and diverse patient populations. References [1] Knopman DS, Laskowitz DT, Koltai DC, Charvet LE, Becker JH, Federman AD, et al. RECOVER‐NEURO: study protocol for a multi‐center, multi‐arm, phase 2, randomized, active comparator trial evaluating three interventions for cognitive dysfunction in post‐acute sequelae of SARS‐CoV‐2 infection (PASC). Trials 2024;25:326. https://doi.org/10.1186/s13063‐024‐08156‐z. [2] Pilloni G, Vogel‐Eyny A, Lustberg M, Best P, Malik M, Walton‐Masters L, et al. Tolerability and feasibility of at‐home remotely supervised transcranial direct current stimulation (RS‐ tDCS): Single‐center evidence from 6,779 sessions. Brain Stimulat 2022;15:707–16. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.brs.2022.04.014. [3] Charvet LE, Shaw MT, Bikson M, Woods AJ, Knotkova H. Supervised transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) at home: A guide for clinical research and practice. Brain Stimulat 2020;13:686–93. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.brs.2020.02.011. [4] Shaw MT, Best P, Frontario A, Charvet LE. Telerehabilitation benefits patients with multiple sclerosis in an urban setting. J Telemed Telecare 2019:1357633X19861830. https://doi.org/10.1177/1357633X19861830. [5] Pilloni G, Bikson M, Badran BW, George MS, Kautz S, Okano AH, et al. Update on the Use of Transcranial Electrical Brain Stimulation to Manage Acute and Chronic COVID‐19 Symptoms. Front Hum Neurosci 2020. https://doi.org/10.3389/fnhum.2020.595567. [6] Bikson M, Hanlon CA, Woods AJ, Gillick BT, Charvet L, Lamm C, et al. Guidelines for TMS/tES clinical services and research through the COVID‐19 pandemic. Brain Stimulat 2020;13:1124–49. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.brs.2020.05.010. Disclosures Nothing to be disclosed by any author(s).
