N2  -  Abstract Background‐Objectives Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) has generated some promising outcomes in primary progressive aphasia (PPA). The logopenic variant (lv‐PPA), a frequent phenotype often related to underlying Alzheimer pathology, erodes the temporal‐parietal junction (TPJ) generating impaired lexical processing, rapidly extending to semantic deficits. Positive tDCS effects have been reported in several small‐cohort studies but there is need for rigorous sham‐controlled double‐blind investigations to substantiate, or not, beneficial effects. Methods We used a sham‐controlled double‐blind counter‐balanced crossover design with 12 clinically and imaging‐characterized lv‐PPA patients applying, according to the principle of interhemispheric rivalry, anodal and cathodal tDCS over the left and right TPJ, respectively, as compared to sham. The three tDCS sessions (1.59mA, 0.06mA/cm2, 20min) were guided by MRI‐based stereotaxic neuronavigation ensuring shortest/straight path to the cortical targets (MNI coordinates [left‐anodal: x=‐64, y=‐38, z=6], [right‐cathodal: x=64, y=‐38, z=6]). A letter fluency (lexical access), a picture‐naming (lexical/semantic access), and a semantic‐matching task were applied before and after tDCS. Computational modeling was used to characterize predicted cortical tDCS current distribution. Results Comparisons of post/pre‐tDCS results did not show language improvement in any task. Finite element models showed impact for both tDCS modalities on the TPJ, but with lower radial ﬁeld‐strength when atrophy was implemented in the model. Correlation analyses indicated that lesser aphasia severity and shorter disease duration are associated with more efficient tDCS outcomes. Discussion The absence of significant tDCS effects mitigates previous findings. Such ‘null results’ contribute to fight against publication‐selection biases, and they allow for unveiling/discussing factors influencing tDCS efficiency such as severity of atrophy/language impairment and tDCS targets. Our findings indicate that patients in early stages with relatively mild aphasia/atrophy might be best candidates for potential therapy use. Investigations systematically exploring parameters impacting stimulation effects are indispensable to provide proof‐of‐concept for tDCS solutions. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 9. Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) Keywords Logopenic Primary Progressive Aphasia, tDCS, Language
