N2  -  Abstract A11: Presented at the 2024 NYC Neuromodulation Conference Synopsis We hypothesize that home‐based transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) is an effective noninvasive intervention for managing neuropsychiatric symptoms (NPS) in older adults with Alzheimer’s Disease and Related Dementias (ADRD). By delivering low‐intensity electrical currents to the brain, tDCS modulates neuronal excitability and promotes neuroplasticity, leading to improvements in mood, behavior, and cognitive function. Background Neuropsychiatric symptoms (NPS), such as agitation and depression, are common in individuals with ADRD [1]. Traditional treatments, such as antipsychotics, carry risks, highlighting the need for safer, nonpharmacological options [2]. Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) is a promising, noninvasive, and nonpharmacological option that modulates brain activity to reduce NPS [3]. Home‐based, remotely supervised tDCS provides added convenience and enhances adherence by enabling patients to receive treatment in their homes [4]. However, very few studies have specifically investigated the efficacy on NPS in ADRD [5,6]. This study was designed to address this gap by investigating the effects of remotely supervised tDCS in managing NPS in older adults with mild to moderate ADRD. Methods The study used a single‐center, double‐blind, randomized, sham‐controlled design to evaluate efficacy of daily 20‐minute home‐based tDCS sessions (Monday to Friday) in managing NPS in older adults with chronic pain. Forty community‐dwelling patients with early‐stage ADRD were randomly assigned (1:1) to either active tDCS (n = 20) or sham tDCS (n = 20). Home‐based tDCS was administered daily for 20 minutes, using the Soterix 1x1 tDCS mini‐CT Stimulator (Soterix Medical Inc.), with saline‐soaked sponge electrodes for comfort. A 2 mA current, known for its analgesic effects, was applied with the anode over the left M1 and the cathode over the right supraorbital region, following evidence‐based guidelines. The device powered off automatically after each session, and caregivers removed and stored the equipment. Sham tDCS followed the same procedure but delivered only 30 seconds of stimulation, replicating the tingling sensation experienced in active tDCS to make the sham intervention indistinguishable from real treatment. Participants were informed that they might or might not feel sensations, and the device settings were identical for both groups. Stimulation parameters and duration adhered to evidence‐based guidelines and prior research. All participants responded to a questionnaire to provide demographic information, including age, gender, body mass index (BMI; kg/m2), race, marital status, and education. NPS were assessed at four time points: immediately after treatment and at 1, 2, and 3 months post intervention, using two scales: (a) Cohen‐Mansfield Agitation Inventory (CMAI) long form (b) Neuropsychiatric Inventory‐Questionnaire (NPI‐Q). Given the small sample size of this pilot study, Hedges' g was used to assess the intervention's effect size, as it corrects for the bias in Cohen's d due to small samples. The 95% confidence interval (CI) for Hedges' g was also reported. Additionally, Cliff’s δ was calculated, which is suitable for ordinal data in this study. One‐sided p‐values were computed using permutation tests, with the alternative hypothesis that the active tDCS group would show a greater negative change than the sham tDCS group. Statistical significance was set at p < .10. Results The sham and active tDCS groups were similar in demographics, including age (74.15 ± 6.16 years‐sham tDCS and 71.90 ± 8.97 years active tDCS), gender, BMI (BMI was 26.92 ± 5.21 kg/m2), and education level, with no significant baseline differences (p > .10). The results showed significantly greater improvement in the following neuropsychiatric symptoms: scratching (p =.052, Hedges’ g = ‐0.60, Cliff’s δ = ‐0.41), nighttime behaviors (p = .041, Hedges’ g = ‐0.62, Cliff’s δ = ‐0.41), and appetite/eating changes (p = .010, Hedges’ g = ‐0.78, Cliff’s δ = ‐0.41). From baseline to 3 months post‐intervention, active tDCS significantly reduced the severity of nighttime behaviors (p = .080; Hedges’ g = ‐0.50 [CI: ‐1.13, 0.14]; Cliff’s δ = ‐0.34 [CI: ‐0.67, 0.01]), as well as the frequency (p = .069; Hedges’ g = ‐0.52 [CI: ‐1.15, 0.12]; Cliff’s δ = ‐0.20 [CI: ‐0.45, ‐0.08]) and severity (p = .010; Hedges’ g = ‐0.78 [CI: ‐1.43, ‐0.13]; Cliff’s δ = ‐0.41 [CI: ‐0.56, ‐0.10]) of appetite/eating changes. Discussion This study presents promising initial results for using home‐based, remotely supervised tDCS to manage NPS in older adults with ADRD, including nighttime behaviors, changes in appetite, and scratching. Active tDCS may have targeted neural mechanisms [7] related to nighttime disturbances, such as agitation, anxiety, or sleep issues, commonly seen in persons with ADRD. The results suggest that tDCS could be an effective tool for managing sleep disturbances in clinical settings. The reduction in nighttime behaviors points to tDCS as a potential adjunct to existing treatments, helping to improve quality of life for both patients and caregivers by address‐ ing these challenging symptoms. Larger studies with more participants are needed to explore various tDCS doses and their long‐term effects on NPS. References [1] Achterberg W, Lautenbacher S, Husebo B, Erdal A, Herr K. Pain in dementia. Pain Rep. Jan‐Feb 2020;5(1):e803. doi:10.1097/pr9.0000000000000803 [2] Cummings J. The Role of Neuropsychiatric Symptoms in Research Diagnostic Criteria for Neurodegenerative Diseases. Am J Geriatr Psychiatry. Apr 2021;29(4):375‐383. doi:10.1016/j.jagp.2020.07.011 [3] Aderinto, N., Olatunji, G., Muili, A. et al. A narrative review of non‐invasive brain stimulation techniques in neuropsychiatric disorders: current applications and future directions. Egypt J Neurol Psychiatry Neurosurg 60, 50 (2024). https://doi.org/10.1186/s41983‐024‐00824‐w [4] Ahn H, Sorkpor S, Miao H, et al. Home‐based self‐administered transcranial direct current stimulation in older adults with knee osteoarthritis pain: An open‐label study. J Clin Neurosci. 2019;66:61‐65. doi:10.1016/j.jocn.2019.05.023 [5] Martorella G, Miao H, Wang D, et al. Feasibility, Acceptability, and Efficacy of Home‐Based Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation on Pain in Older Adults with Alzheimer's Disease and Related Dementias: A Randomized Sham‐Controlled Pilot Clinical Trial. J Clin Med. Jan 4 2023;12(2)doi:10.3390/jcm12020401 [6] Teixeira PEP, Alawdah L, Alhassan HAA, et al. The Analgesic Effect of Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) combined with Physical Therapy on Common Musculoskeletal Conditions: A Systematic Review and Meta‐Analysis. Princ Pract Clin Res. Jan‐Apr 2020;6(1):23‐26. doi:10.21801/ppcrj.2020.61.5 [7] Kai K, Hashimoto M, Amano K, Tanaka H, Fukuhara R, Ikeda M. Relationship between eating disturbance and dementia severity in patients with Alzheimer’s disease. PloS one. 2015;10(8):e0133666. Disclosures The authors declare no conflicts of interest related to this study. This research was funded by the National Institutes of Health/National Institute of Nursing Research Grant R15NR018050 and R01NR019051.
