N2  -  Transcranial electrical stimulation (tES) techniques like transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) and transcranial alternating current stimulation (tACS) are increasingly used in research and clinical settings to enhance the effects of cognitive training. Recent studies suggested that improvement of behavioral performance is associated with tES‐induced modulation of neuronal activity and cortical oscillations as well as connectivity. Thus, it may also represent a promising tool for reconstitution of cognitive functions in the context of memory decline related to aging, as well as Alzheimer's disease (AD) and its precursors, particularly if combined with training. In this contribution, I will present a series of studies using anodal tDCS, as well as tACS in the theta range, in combination with cognitive training in older adults [1‐3] and patients with mild cognitive impairment (MCI) [4, 5], which is regarded as a prodromal stage of AD. First promising results with regard to enhanced learning ability and retention, as well as cognitive abilities were seen, but duration and repetition of stimulation, as well as the optimal combination of training with tES protocols still needs to be systematically evaluated. In sum, tES could provide the exciting possibility to reconstitute cognitive functions in aging and in memory disorders due to neurodegenerative disease. However, evidence from randomized sham‐controlled clinical trials is still scarce, and future studies now have to elucidate whether tES can be used in the clinical routine to prevent further cognitive decline in neurodegenerative diseases and whether beneficial effects from experimental studies translate into long‐term improvement in activities of daily life.
