N2  -  Abstract Introduction: Cognitive impairment (CI) is considered to be an enduring core feature of schizophrenia (SZ) with a crucial influence on long‐term functional outcome. Despite the development of pharmacological and rehabilitation methods, cognitive dysfunction shows mostly low improvements with treatment in psychiatric disorders and creates an actual and challenging problem for specialists. Cognitive training (CT) represents a well‐established non‐pharmacological treatment of CI in SZ and a large number of studies have proven its benefit. However, only moderate improvement in cognition, and even less impact on daily functioning, was shown. Therefore, augmentation strategies could increase the effect of CT. Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) is a brain stimulation technique that has shown great potential for the enhancement of cognition. Methods: A one‐week, randomized, two‐parallel‐group, double‐blind, placebo‐controlled trial. Overall 5 sessions of tDCS with CT were applied during one week. Patients with psychotic disorders were cognitively assessed by RBANS test at baseline and after one week of treatment. The tDCS anode was placed over the F3 (corresponding to the left DLPFC). A reference cathodal electrode was placed over the Fp2. For active stimulation, we administer 2mA (current density 0.08 mA/m2) direct current lasting 30 minutes. Placebo stimulation with the same position of electrodes included only the initial 30s ramping phase. CT was carried out with REHACOM program (which included training in processing speed, attention, and working memory) and lasted 60 minutes. Results and Conclusions: The trial was performed with 20 patients (2 persons from the active group withdrew the study). No difference between the index scores was reached, and therefore we cannot reject the possibility of the identical effect of CT with and without tDCS on cognitive performance. However, the longer application of CT with more participants is needed for future research. Supported by PharmaBrain No. CZ.02.1.01./0.0/0.0/16_0250007444 and CNPS. Keywords: transcranial direct current stimulation, cognitive training, schizophrenia, cognitive deficit
