N2  -  Symposium title Efficacy and hemodynamic responses of electrical and magnetic stimulation in Alzheimer’s treatment Abstract Millions of people worldwide are affected by a progressive neurodegenerative dementia. Previous studies have suggested that transcranial alternating current stimulation (tACS) may extend the positive cognitive effects of performing tutored cognitive exercise. This study aims to explore the immediate and long‐term cognitive effects of tACS applied simultaneously with cognitive exercises in individuals with mild to moderate dementia. Participants were assigned to receive real tACS or sham stimulation using stratified randomization considering age, sex, and severity. Participants received two 30‐minute treatments/day, 5 days/week for 4 weeks. Alzheimer disease assessment scale‐cognitive subscale (ADAS‐Cog) scores were measured at baseline, post‐treatment, and approximately 2‐month follow‐up. Soterix device was used to apply electrical stimulation with electrodes placed over F3 and Fp2. Participants in both groups received tutored cognitive exercises during real/sham tACS treatment using MindTrigger app. A total of 35 participants, 17 in real tACS group, completed the study. Both groups showed significant improvement in ADAS‐Cog score from baseline to post‐treatment using paired t‐tests: p = 0.037 and 0.041 for real and sham groups, respectively. To evaluate the long‐term effects of tACS, independent sample t‐test was used to compare real tACS with sham ADAS‐Cog score changes from post‐treatment to the approximately 2‐month follow‐up. A significant difference (p=0.049) was found between the groups. This implies real tACS, unlike sham, may extend the positive cognitive effects of the treatment. The real tACS group showed an average improvement of 1.67 points in ADAS‐Cog scores from post‐treatment to follow‐up, compared to the average decline of 1.72 points in the sham group. These findings suggest real tACS, when combined with cognitive exercise, may improve cognitive function in individuals with dementia immediately and with longer‐lasting effects. Further research is needed to explore the optimal parameters of electrical stimulation. Research Category and Technology and Methods Translational Research: 8. Transcranial Alternating Current Stimulation (tACS) Keywords dementia, tACS, cognitive exercises, Alzheimer's
