N2  -  Background: Transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) is a non‐invasive type of brain stimulation that uses electrical currents to modulate neuronal activity. A small number of studies have investigated the effects of tDCS on cognition in patients with Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI) and Alzheimer's Disease (AD), and have demonstrated variable efficacies. However, emerging evidence suggests that tDCS is most effective when applied to active brain circuits. Exercise is known to increase cortical excitability and improve brain network connectivity. As such, exercise may be an effective, yet previously unexplored primer for tDCS to improve cognition in MCI and mild AD. We describe a clinical trial to investigate the effects of a combined exercise priming and tDCS intervention in patients with MCI and mild AD. Methods: Patients will be randomized to receive 10 sessions over 2 weeks of either exercise primed tDCS, exercise primed sham tDCS, or tDCS alone in a blinded, parallel‐design trial. Those randomized to an exercise intervention will receive personalized exercise prescriptions to achieve a moderate‐intensity dosage, a level sufficient to increase cortical excitability. Our primary aim is to assess the efficacy of primed tDCS for improving global cognition using the Montreal Cognitive Assessment. Our secondary aim is to evaluate the efficacy of primed tDCS for improving specific cognitive domains (memory & executive function) and neuropsychiatric symptoms. We will also explore whether primed tDCS is associated with an increase in markers of neurogenesis and angiogenesis, and if changes in these markers are correlated with cognitive improvement. Results and Conclusions: Preliminary data will be presented. This proof‐of‐concept study may identify a previously unexplored, non‐invasive, non‐pharmacological combination intervention that improves cognitive symptoms in patients with MCI and mild AD. Findings from this study may also identify potential mechanisms of tDCS to preserve cognition in MCI and mild AD. Keywords: transcranial direct current stimulation, exercise, memory, primer
