N2  -  Introduction: Alzheimer disease (AD) is one of the most devastating neurological disorder of many neurological conditions due to its social and economic impact. Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) can enable stimulation of the brain and modulate neuronal excitability and enhance cortical function. The therapeutic effect of rTMS with cognitive training (CT) in mild AD has proved in the previous randomized controlled study. In contrast, the cognitive benefit in moderate to severe AD patients has not proved yet. We evaluate the cognitive effect of rTMS‐CT in patients with moderate to severe AD and compare its therapeutic magnitude with mild AD. Method(s): We recruited AD patients who were diagnosed with Alzheimer's disease by DSM‐IV criteria and received rTMS‐CT in our hospital. Most of the participants had been enrolled in our previous two RCTs. The others who wanted to get rTMS‐CT were included this analyses. All participants were undertaken brain MRIs for a navigation system and neuropsychological assessments including ADAS‐cog, MMSE, and geriatric depression scale (GDS). The rTMS protocols were configured for six cortical areas (both dorsolateral prefrontal and parietal somatosensory associated cortices and Broca's and Wernicke's areas; 10Hz, 90‐110% intensity, and 5 days/week for 6 weeks). Neuropsychological assessments were performed before, immediately after, and 6 weeks after the end of treatment. We analyzed improvement of cognitive function and depression after rTMS‐CT in mild (MMSE score= 21 26) and moderate to severe (MMSE score < 20) AD. Result(s): Cognitive function assessed by ADAS‐cog after rTMS‐CT in 6w and 12w has significantly improved compared with the baseline, prior to rTMS‐CT in both groups (34 mild, 13, moderate to severe). Conclusion(s): rTMS‐CT may be a potential treatment modality to slow or delay cognitive decline in AD. Keywords: Copyright © 2018
