DO  -  10.1016/j.brs.2018.12.009
N2  -  Progressive Supranuclear Palsy (PSP) is a neurodegenerative condition impacting the basal ganglia, the brain stem and the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC). Importantly, PSP patients suffer language impairments, such as lexical and semantic access correlating with left DLPFC atrophy. Network connectivity is also altered in PSP and a decrease in functional connectivity in prefrontal regions correlates with lower cognitive performances. Language improvements with transcranial brain stimulation technologies have been reported in neurodegenerative conditions (e.g. Alzheimers’ disease and Primary Progressive Aphasias). However, to date, no study has investigated similar effects in PSP patients. Using a sham‐controlled double‐blind crossover design we tested the impact of transcranial Direct Current Stimulation (tDCS) on a cohort of PSP patients. In three separate sessions, we evaluated the ability to boost left‐sided language‐related areas with left anodal or right cathodal prefrontal tDCS delivered over the DLPFC, compared to sham stimulation. Tasks assessing lexical/semantic access (Category judgment, Letter fluency) were recorded as behavioral outcome measures. PSP patients were significantly impaired compared to healthy controls on both tasks. Moreover, outcomes contrasting post vs. pre‐stimulation performance across tDCS conditions revealed robust language improvement on semantic category judgment following right‐cathodal tDCS. In parallel, restricted analysis on letter fluency showed marginal improvements following left‐anodal tDCS. A computational Finite Element Model of tDCS current distribution corroborated the intended impact of left anodal and right cathodal tDCS on the targeted DLPFC. Our findings provide first‐time evidence on tDCS‐driven language improvement in PSP patients. These results contribute proof‐of‐concept for the use of tDCS in this neurodegenerative condition, and set the stage for future multi‐day stimulation regimes leading to longer lasting therapeutic effects, promoted by neuroplasticity. Acknowledgements: Marc Teichmann has received support from ‘PSP‐France’. Clara Sanches is funded by PhD funds from the ‘Fondation Recherche Alzheimer (FRA)’. The activities of Dr. Antoni Valero‐Cabré research group are supported by research grants: ‘IHU‐A‐ICM‐Translationnel’, ‘Agence Nationale de la Recherche (ANR)’, ‘projet Générique OSCILOSCOPUS’ and the ‘PHRC NEGLECT’.
