DO  -  10.1016/j.brs.2024.12.134
N2  -  Symposium title Non‐invasive brain stimulation for neuropsychiatric disorders Abstract Transcranial alternating current stimulation (tACS) offers a non‐invasive approach to modulate brain oscillations and address cognitive deficits in neurodegenerative disorders such as Alzheimer’s disease (AD) and dementia with Lewy bodies (DLB). In a randomized, double‐blind, sham‐controlled crossover trial involving AD patients, we observed that γ‐tACS applied over the precuneus significantly enhanced episodic memory and cholinergic transmission, correlating with increases in gamma power in posterior brain regions. Clinical improvements were influenced by genetic factors and disease stage. Similarly, in a study with DLB patients, we found that α‐tACS over the occipital cortex significantly improved visuospatial and executive functions without affecting verbal episodic memory. This intervention also increased cholinergic transmission and shifted EEG power from delta to alpha frequencies, indicating effective neural engagement. Together, these findings suggest that tACS could be a valuable therapeutic tool in managing cognitive impairments in AD and DLB, with tailored stimulation protocols enhancing specific brain oscillations linked to each disorder. Further research is needed to optimize stimulation settings and assess long‐term benefits in larger cohorts. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 8. Transcranial Alternating Current Stimulation (tACS) Keywords Transcranial alternate current stimulation, Dementia with Lewy bodies, Alzheimer’s disease, Electroencephalography
