DO  -  10.1016/j.jalz.2019.06.086
N2  -  Background: The Results were discordant in different studies about the efficacy，parametres and the underlying mechanisms of repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) combined with cognitive training (CT) on Alzheimer’s disease (AD). To assess the effect of rTMS‐CT on cognition, the activities of daily life (ADL)，neuropsychiatric behavioral symptoms (BPSD) and the metabolites beneath the stimulated areas of the brain in patients with Alzheimer’s disease and to investigate the correlation of metabolic changes measured by 1H MRS with clinical outcomes after treatment. Methods: Thirty consecutive patients with mild or moderate Alzheimer’s disease were enrolled and randomly divided into two intervention groups: the real rTMS with CT group (real group) and the sham rTMS with CT group (sham group). 10Hz rTMS was first stimulated the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) and then the left lateral temporal Lobe (LTL) for 20 minutes each day, lasted for four weeks. Every patient underwent neuropsychological assessment at baseline (T0), immediate after treatment (T1) and 4 weeks after treatment (T2). The levels ratios of N‐acetylaspartate (NAA)/Creatine (Cr), myo‐inositol (mI)/Cr and choline (Cho)/Cr in the stimulated cortex were measured by proton magnetic resonance spectroscopy (1H‐MRS), at T0 and T1. The change from To at T1 and T2 was cacluated by analysis of covariance (ANCOVA). Results: Twenty eight patients had been treated with rTMS‐CT for 4 weeks, with two subjects quitted after treated several times in sham group. Compared with the sham group, the cognitive function and behavior in real rTMS group improved significantly at T1 and T2. Compared to that of the sham group, NAA/Cr ratio in the left DLPFC elevated significantly (p = 0.045), but only appeared an increasing tendency in the left LTL (p = 0.162). The change of the NAA/Cr ratio in left DLPFC showed a negative correlation with the change of cognitive scales of Alzheimer’s Disease Assessment Scale (ADAS‐Cog). Conclusions: This study indicates possible modest rTMS‐CT effect on prevention of clinical and neuronal functional deterioration in left DLPFC of the AD patients. The left DLPFC would be better for the candidate area than the left LTL.
