DO  -  10.1002/oby.24195
N2  -  Background: Obesity is associated with an increased risk of cognitive impairment. Repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS) has been developed into a powerful tool that utilizes magnetic fluxes to non‐invasively stimulate the human cortex. The aim of this study is to evaluate the effects of rTMS, delivered to the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC), on cognitive function in obesity. Methods: The study was performed in a randomized sham controlled parallel design. A total of 60 obese subjects (body mass index [BMI] ≥25 kg/m2) aged between 18 and 65 years with normal cognitive function were enrolled, and 54 completed 4‐week follow‐up (29 in the TMS group and 25 in the control group). rTMS sessions took place every 3 days for 2 weeks, a total of 4 sessions targeting the left DLPFC with a frequency of 10Hz and intensity of 110% of the individual's motor threshold. All subjects underwent 3T brain MRI scanning before and after rTMS session. The primary outcome was the change in cognitive function using the Korean version of the Consortium to Establish a Registry for Alzheimer's Disease (CERAD‐K), and secondary outcomes were structural brain change. Results: The repeated‐measures ANCOVA adjusted for age and education revealed significant improvement after rTMS in verbal fluency (p=0.01), word list recognition (p=0.03), and total CERAD‐K score (p=0.01) compared with the control group. For Voxel‐based morphometry (VBM) analysis, sham stimulation group showed smaller volumes in frontotemporal gray matter, parahippocampal gyrus, and hippocampus compared with rTMS group (all comparisons p<0.05, FDR corrected). Conclusions: In the present study, rTMS delivered to the left DLPFC improved cognitive function in adults with obesity, suggesting the potential application of rTMS to reduce the risk for cognitive disorders in obesity.
