DO  -  10.1016/j.brs.2018.12.715
N2  -  Introduction: Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) has the potential to improve symptoms of Alzheimer's disease (AD). We proposed a study taking into account the different paradigms and regions of interest previously studied that show that rTMS can produce changes as well as to improve the cognitive performance and behavior reflected in the functionality. Objectives: To compare the clinical effects of rTMS using two protocols: 1) single‐site stimulation applied to the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) and, 2) a six‐region (multi‐site) stimulation approach that included: right DLPFC and left, left frontal gyrus and left posterior region of the superior temporal lobe (Broca and Wernicke areas, respectively), and cortices of right and left parietal somatosensory association. Method: We performed a single‐blind randomized clinical trial in patients diagnosed with mild and moderate AD. We administered 15 sessions (3 weeks) of 1500 pulses per session at a frequency of 5 Hz. Repeated‐measures ANOVA analysis were carried out. Results: 19 patients, without dropping out the study, met the inclusion criteria (CPFDLi group: 10 patients, multi‐site group: 9 patients). Both protocols were equally competent in the clinical improvement in cognition, behavior and functionality after 3 weeks of treatment and the effect was maintained after 4 weeks without treatment. We confirmed that not only the multi‐site protocol had to show significant differences in the language because it includes specific areas of it. Conclusions: When applying rTMS for the first time at a frequency of 5 Hz in EA, we found that both protocols were equally beneficial. Because there is no clinical superiority, the ease of locating only the CPFDLi could be an advantage over multi‐site stimulation, which is explained by the local connectivity and/or superposition of striatal networks. In this way the direct rTMS of the CPFDLi would have effects on interconnected networks. Keywords: alzheimer,rtms,alzheimers
