DO  -  10.1016/j.brs.2018.12.519
N2  -  Cognitive and mobility impairment are common in seniors and result in significant disability. Emerging evidence suggests that executive function is involved in gait regulation. HF‐rTMS is a relatively safe non‐invasive brain stimulation technique that has been shown to enhance motor learning and working memory. However, the role of HF‐rTMS has not been adequately explored in modulating the motoric‐cognitive risk syndrome, which increases the risk for Alzheimer disease. We aim to present the design and preliminary results of an ongoing study exploring the effect of bilateral prefrontal HF‐ rTMS on the motoric‐cognitive risk syndrome in seniors with executive impairment but no dementia. Methods: Forty seniors with cognitive complaint and impaired trail making test‐B are being recruited to the study from memory clinic setting excluding those with dementia, severe depression or other neurological illnesses that directly impair gait. Baseline clinical, cognitive and gait assessments are done and patients are randomized to active vs. sham rTMS. Five consecutive daily active or sham sessions of HF‐rTMS (20 Hz, 2000 pulses) to the right then left prefrontal areas are applied. Patients and assessors are blinded to the study assignment. Cognitive and gait measures are repeated immediately after the last session (day 5) and at 7 days post intervention. Results: Ten participants have completed the study so far. HF‐rTMS was well tolerated with only one drop out due to head discomfort from the active arm. Preliminary analysis shows significantly higher performance in memory encoding and a trend of higher performance in semantic dual‐task gait at 7 days post 5 sessions of HF‐rTMS in the active compared to the sham group. Conclusions: These preliminary results are encouraging. Implications and future direction will be discussed. Keywords: rTMS, high‐frequency, Motoric‐cognitive, seniors
