N2  -  Background: Deficits in frontal lobe functions including deficits in working memory are common across all stages of Alzheimer's disease (AD). Working memory has been associated with frontal cortical oscillations in theta and gamma bands and in particular the modulation of gamma amplitude by theta phase (theta‐gamma coupling). These neurophysiological mechanisms depend upon robust synaptic neuroplasticity. Paired associative stimulation (PAS) involves repetitive pairing of electrical stimulation of the median nerve with transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) pulse 25 ms later to contralateral Dorsolateral Prefrontal Cortex (DLPFC) and simulates the induction of long‐term potentiation, a prototype of synaptic neuroplasticity. Methods: We are presenting baseline pilot data on 12 participants with early AD (Mini Mental Status Exam score ≥16) and 11 healthy participants who were enrolled in a randomized double‐blind controlled trial to receive a 2‐week course of active PAS (PAS‐25) or control condition (PAS‐100) and have their working memory assessed pre‐PAS. PAS was combined with TMS‐EEG to assess cortical evoked activity and theta‐gamma coupling in the DLPFC before and after PAS. Results: Preliminary findings suggest that compared with healthy participants, participants with AD have (1) impaired performance on the N‐back task, (2) impaired DLPFC neuroplasticity as measured by PAS induced cortical evoked activity, (3) but preserved ability to experience potentiation of theta‐gamma coupling in response to PAS. Conclusions: Our findings suggest that individuals with early AD are likely to benefit from brain stimulation interventions that enhance theta‐gamma coupling and consequently could enhance working memory.
