N2  -  Symposium title Advanced Brain Stimulation in Neuropsychiatry: Bridging the Gap from Bench to Clinical Practice Abstract Since the advent of COVID‐19 in December 2019, the pandemic has spread globally. Vaccines and potential herd immunity have mitigated acute respiratory symptoms, but persistent cognitive dysfunction, known as "brain fog," chronic fatigue, insomnia, and depressive moods persist, known as Long COVID. This condition has become a significant social problem. Against this background, we aim to investigate a novel treatment for Long COVID, a condition with persistent cognitive impairment, chronic fatigue, insomnia and depressive moods after acute COVID‐19. The treatment is transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) therapy, which will be evaluated in a randomized controlled trial (RCT) with 70 participants. The primary outcome is the MADRS score and the study will examine the correlation between clinical epidemiologic data and treatment improvement rates. The study will target participant who have developed psychiatric disorders after COVID‐19 infection. This RCT will be randomized using dynamic adaptive allocation with age, sex and baseline MADRS score as factors. The study will analyze differences between the active TMS and sham TMS interventions for each clinical assessment outcome using a mixed model for repeated measures analysis. To date, 35 participants with long COVID have been enrolled in the study and exactly half of the target number has been completed. The RCT is ongoing and the intervention is not yet open. The last participant is expected to complete the study by next summer, followed by statistical analysis. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords Long COVID, brain fog, Cognitive impairment, rTMS neuromodulation
