DO  -  10.1016/j.clinph.2023.03.318
N2  -  Objectives: Alzheimer's disease (AD) is a common neurodegenerative disorder among geriatric population, typically treated with drugs that only temporarily slow cognitive decline. However, repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) has emerged as a new and innovative strategy for treating AD. In this framework, this study evaluates the effects of a 6‐week protocol of cognitive training combined with rTMS (rTMS‐COG) in 72 AD using neuropsychological and electroencephalographic data. Content: A randomized, double‐blind, sham‐controlled trial was designed, and the patients were randomly assigned in three groups: A) real‐rTMS stimulation and cognitive training; B) sham‐TMS stimulation and cognitive training; C) sham‐TMS stimulation and pseudo‐cognitive training. An eight‐coil rTMS was positioned over the six brain regions activated during the performance of cognitive tasks. Small World (SW) parameters were used to model brain functional architecture. No significant SW modulation was detected at 40‐week follow‐up (T2) in the Group A, indicating that there was no worsening of patient’s condition and highlighting the crucial role of rTMS‐COG rehabilitation treatment. Moreover, a negative correlation between the cognitive performance (ADAS‐Cog) and delta SW, and a positive correlation between the ADAS‐Cog and alpha 1 SW were obtained. Lower delta SW indicated a worse cognitive condition, while lower alpha 1 SW indicated an improving cognitive state, indicating the possible role of SW as a diagnostic biomarker of AD. Additionally, a significant negative correlation was found between ADAS‐Cog score improvement and baseline alpha 2 SW, suggesting the possibility of predicting patient’s recovery by the analysis of EEG data at the beginning of the training session. Keywords: Alzheimer; Cognitive training; EEG; LORETA; Small World; rTMS.
