DO  -  10.1016/j.brs.2023.01.376
N2  -  Abstract Alzheimer’s Disease (AD) is characterized by memory loss, with brain structural and functional dysfunction involving the Default Mode Network (DMN), for which the Precuneus (PC) is a key node. Recently, our group showed that 20‐Hz repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS) over the PC increases long‐term memory performance in AD, suggesting the PC is the ideal target for stimulation to slow down cognitive decline. Here we proposed a randomized double‐blind pilot study to determine neurobiological alterations reflected in structural and functional changes after 24 weeks of PC‐rTMS in patients with mild‐to‐moderate AD. Fourteen patients were randomly assigned to treatment with rTMS (Real, N=7) or placebo (Sham, N=7). Both groups received an intensive 2‐weeks course with daily rTMS sessions, followed by a maintenance phase in which rTMS has been applied once a week for 24 weeks. Each rTMS session consisted of forty, 2‐second trains delivered at 20 Hz that were spaced out by 28 seconds, for a total of 1600 stimuli in 20 minutes. Before and after the treatment structural and functional MRIs were collected. Voxel‐based morphometry analysis showed Gray Matter (GM) loss in the PC, parietal and frontal areas after the treatment specifically for the Sham Group, while both groups showed GM loss in the temporal lobes (p<0.05 FWE‐corrected). Moreover, an increase in functional connectivity (FC) in several nodes of DMN (p<0.05, FDR‐corrected) in the Real Group has been shown. Additionally, a decrease of FC between PC and left superior parietal lobule has been also observed after rTMS in the Real Group. No significant results have been found for the Sham Group. Our results showing GM conservation and FC changes affecting both local and network‐to‐network connectivity dynamics in the Real Group trigger the possibility of using rTMS to increase brain plasticity in AD patients by manipulating distributed network connectivity patterns. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords: TMS, NEUROIMAGING, ALZHEIMER'S DISEASE, PRECUNEUS
