DO  -  10.1177/154596832311594
N2  -  Approximately 30% of individuals affected by COVID‐19 including asymptomatic cases, may experience long‐term sequelae including fatigue and cognitive impairment (long COVID). Early MRI and 18FDG‐PET evidence showed reduction in gray matter thickness and hypometabolism in the orbitofrontal cortex. Using transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) we have demonstrated in patients who developed fatigue and dysexecutive syndrome after severe COVID‐19 a remarkable impairment of GABABergic activity within the primary motor cortex (M1), as demonstrated by altered long‐interval intracortical inhibition (LICI), and reduced cholinergic activity as measured with short‐latency afferent inhibition (SAI). Abnormal LICI is a recognized biomarker of fronto‐temporal dementia, while reduced SAI is a neurophysiological hallmark of Alzheimer's disease. Subsequently, we demonstrated similar alterations in patients with persistent fatigue and cognitive complaints after mild symptomatic COVID‐19. In a randomized, placebo‐controlled, double‐blind clinical trial on 34 patients, we tested the effects of palmitoylethanolamide co‐ultramicronized with luteolin (PEA‐LUT), an endocannabinoid‐like lipid mediator able to enhance GABA‐ergic transmission and to reduce neuroinflammation, on LICI. PEA‐LUT restored impaired LICI and promoted cortical plasticity. Central fatigue might be correlated to a reduced activity in cortical areas of frontal lobe upstream M1 involved in motor planning and preparation, such as supplementary motor area (SMA). In a further study on 18 long COVID patients we assessed by means of TMSEEG cortical activity in SMA and M1. We observed, as compared to a control population, reduced amplitude of TMS‐ boosted cortical oscillatory activity for natural frequencies in M1 and SMA (β and γ frequency, respectively). All these data clearly indicate a persistent dysfunction of frontal lobe activity, in patients with fatigue and executive function deficits after COVID‐19.
