N2  -  Symposium title Advancing non‐invasive brain stimulation in geriatric mental health Abstract Background: Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI) is a significant risk factor for the development of Alzheimer’s disease and related dementias. Despite its prevalence, there are limited effective interventions. Intermittent Theta Burst Stimulation (iTBS) has shown potential in modulating cognitive functions, but its efficacy in MCI remains to be systematically evaluated. This study is designed to assess the feasibility and potential efficacy of iTBS in enhancing cognitive function in individuals with MCI. Study Design and Methodology: The study employs a randomized controlled double‐blind cross‐over design, enrolling participants aged 55‐90, including both healthy controls and those diagnosed with MCI. Participants are randomly assigned to receive iTBS targeting either the left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC), left lateral parietal cortex (LPC), or vertex (control site). The iTBS protocol consists of two distinct treatment periods separated by a 4‐6 week washout period followed by a crossover. A single iTBS session is administered daily for 10 days (5 days per week). Participants receive a total of 20 iTBS sessions over 2 treatment periods. Stimulation Parameters: Each iTBS session follows FDA‐approved parameters of 600 pulses delivered intermittently in bursts of 2 seconds of stimulation followed by an 8‐second pause for a total duration of 3.17 minutes. Outcome Measures and Preliminary Findings: Primary outcomes include changes in cognitive function as measured by neuropsychological testing. Exploratory outcomes assess neurophysiological changes with biomarkers, including fMRI, HD‐EEG, and sleep architecture. Although the study is ongoing, preliminary findings suggest differences in fMRI and HD‐EEG activity between active and control groups, alongside good protocol adherence and no serious adverse events reported. Conclusion: We present the design, methodology, and early findings of a clinical trial exploring the potential of iTBS to enhance cognitive function in MCI. The study is intended to generate data that would inform a larger future trial. Research Category and Technology and Methods Clinical Research: 10. Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (TMS) Keywords Cognitive impairment, Biomarkers, Neuroimaging, Neurophysiology
