DO  -  10.1080/21678421.2025.2564539
N2  -  Background: Loss of glutamatergic synapses is a fundamental aspect of ALS pathogenesis that begins at presymptomatic stages. Suggestive of a nodal and causative role, synapse loss is observed across diverse genetic drivers and is a proximal effect of the most common molecular pathology of ALS, TDP‐43 mislocalization and the C9orf72 repeat expansion. Therapies capable of regenerating lost synapses may be efficacious in treating both motor and cognitive symptoms. SPG302 is an orally administered, rapid acting, synaptogenic small molecule. In preclinical studies, SPG302 improved the course of motor symptoms and extended lifespan by 35% in a TDP‐43 model of ALS, and reversed synapse loss and dendritic atrophy in motor and prefrontal cortices in a Ubqln2 ALS/FTD model (DoD supported). SPG302 also rescued cognitive deficits and enhanced recovery of respiratory function in models of Alzheimer's and spinal cord injury, respectively. Spinogenix has completed a Phase 2a study (NCT05882695) of SPG302 in ALS participants, assessing safety, tolerability, and efficacy across neurophysiological, and functional (motor and cognitive). Neurophysiological outcomes included transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) and EEG measures that are sensitive to synaptic function. Methods: Twenty four ALS participants (TRICALS ‐2 to ‐6) were recruited to evaluate 300 mg SPG302 q.d. over an initial 4‐week double‐blind placebo‐controlled (DBPC) period (3:1 active to placebo), followed by a 24‐week open label period. Safety and efficacy outcomes included ALSFRS‐R, resting state EEG, P300, TMS and plasma NfL, as well as cognition function using the Edinburgh Cognitive and Behavioral ALS Screen (ECAS). Results: SPG302 was safe and well tolerated with drug exposure profiles similar to healthy volunteers. Baseline NfL measures showed prediction of outcome, and trends toward improved ECAS scores were observed. During the DBPC period, ALS signature deficits in resting state EEG power were significantly improved with SPG302 compared to placebo and showed a regional correspondence to affected brain regions. Improvement continued into the open label period across multiple frequency bands. TMS revealed a significant increase in resting motor threshold. At 24 weeks, the average change in ALSFRS‐R from baseline was ‐2.7 ± 4.4 points. Comparison of 23 SPG302‐treated subjects to 299 matched synthetic controls in the PRO‐ACT database showed an ALSFRS‐R total score rate of decline of ‐0.63 (95% CI: ‐1.0997, ‐0.1635) over a 24‐week period. This corresponds to a slope difference of 0.39, and a slope ratio of 0.61; a statistically significant slowing (p=0.035). Additionally, the % improvement in the ALSFRS rate of decline at 24 weeks correlated with EEG power changes at 4 and 8 weeks indicating early target engagement trending with 24 week clinical outcome. Discussion: SPG302 was safe and well tolerated in ALS participants and was associated with rapid and significant neurophysiological outcomes vs placebo that correlated with potential benefits in motor function over 24 weeks.
